data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider deprecated sync APIs but still honored the **`CosmosOptionsExtension.EnableSyncOverAsync`** opt-in. In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), **that opt-in is removed entirely**. Every synchronous LINQ operator and `SaveChanges()` call against the Cosmos provider now throws an `InvalidOperationException` at runtime — there is no configuration workaround.

### Affected calls in your code

| Sync (breaks) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `await .ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(…)` | `await .FirstAsync(…)` |
| `.Count()` | `await .CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `await .SaveChangesAsync()` |

> `.Add()` is fine — it's an in-memory tracking call, not a database operation.

### Migrated version

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key things to propagate up the call stack:**
- All callers must `await` these methods — `async` is viral.
- Controller actions should already be `async Task<IActionResult>`, but verify.
- Remove the now-defunct `EnableSyncOverAsync` configuration from your `DbContext` setup.
